You're using Option A: Class and Gender (Marx & Wollstonecraft).

Per the final project brief (KB[2]), this option sets up a core theoretical tension between economic class (Marx) and gender domination (Wollstonecraft). Here's what you are modeling:

Marx emphasizes class struggle as the primary engine of history—your social position as worker or owner determines your worldview, power, and alienation.

Wollstonecraft focuses on gender-based domination, especially within family structures and moral education. For her, even within the working class, women are subject to a second, more hidden form of alienation and subjugation.

You are modeling a social world in which both economic class and gender shape agent behavior and social outcomes—sometimes in conflict. For example:

Does solidarity across class override gendered domination?

Does gender hierarchy persist even in revolutionary settings?

